ologyError Display -> TEST-TOPO-ERRORS (7+ tests). (12) compute_composite_coupling -> TOPO-COMPOSITE acceptance (3 tests). (13) coupling_density_matrix -> TOPO-DENSITY acceptance (4 tests) + TEST-TOPO-PROPTEST (10 properties). (14) fiedler_from_coupling_matrix -> TOPO-SPECTRAL acceptance (4 tests). (15) compute_topology_fitness -> FT-COMPUTE acceptance (4 tests). (16) plan persistence roundtrip -> TEST-TOPO-PERSIST (5 tests). (17) TOTAL: 36+ unit tests, 10+ proptests, 2 E2E scripts (~20 tests), 1 self-bootstrap test. GRAND TOTAL: ~67 tests. This exceeds our quality gate (every public function has >=2 tests).; META-AUDIT: After 4 review passes, the tasks are individually well-specified but I haven't checked the SYSTEM PROPERTIES of the task graph itself. Individual task quality != graph quality. What I need to verify: (1) CRITICAL PATH LENGTH — is the longest dependency chain unnecessarily sequential? Can we parallelize? (2) BOTTLENECK ANALYSIS — which tasks block the most downstream work? Are they correctly prioritized? (3) IMPLEMENTATION ORDERING — does the batch structure match the DoF calibration from spec-first-design? (formal discovery → mechanization → execution). (4) TEST COVERAGE COMPLETENESS — does every non-trivial function have both unit tests AND proptest? (5) CROSS-EPIC DEPENDENCIES — are there implicit dependencies between EPICs that aren't explicitly wired? (6) THE OUTPUT CHAIN — if I follow the execution order, does each task's output become the next task's input seamlessly? No API mismatches?" :op :assert}
